// Chained guarded forward-jumps to a single far join — the pyth `update_*` short-circuit
// shape (`fresh = !stale_a && !stale_b; if (fresh) ...`). Each check, on failure, does
// some work and jumps forward to the join J; on success it falls through to the next check.
//
//   0 (cond check_a) ─true─> 1 (fail_a; goto 6)
//   │ false
//   v
//   2 (cond check_b) ─true─> 3 (fail_b; goto 6)
//   │ false
//   v
//   4 (rest; goto 6)
//   6 (join, sink)
//
// J=6 has preds {1, 3, 4}; J.idom = 0 (every path from 0 reaches it), so J is owned by
// node 0's scope, NOT node 2's. The question is whether the structurer recovers nested
// if/else here or leaves the inner jump as a goto.
cond,0,1,2
code,1,6
cond,2,3,4
code,3,6
code,4,6
code,6
